Enterprise architecture has no shortage of frameworks, methods, and diagramming tools. It's common to hear questions like:
> Should we use EDGY or C4? Is Mermaid replacing both?
The answer is simple:
**They're not competitors.**
EDGY, C4, and Mermaid operate at different levels of abstraction and solve different problems. Rather than competing, they complement one another remarkably well. Together they provide a coherent path from enterprise strategy to running software.
## Three Tools, Three Different Purposes
At a high level:
- **EDGY** helps model the enterprise.
- **C4** helps describe software systems.
- **Mermaid** helps visualize architecture.
Think of them as layers rather than alternatives.
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Strategy["Enterprise Strategy"]
    EDGY["EDGY Enterprise Design"]
    C4["C4 Software Architecture"]
    Mermaid["Mermaid Diagrams"]
    Delivery["Running Software"]
    Strategy --> EDGY
    EDGY --> C4
    C4 --> Mermaid
    Mermaid --> Delivery

Each contributes something different to the overall architecture.

Tool	Purpose	Primary Audience
EDGY	Enterprise design	Business leaders, enterprise architects
C4	Software architecture	Architects and engineering teams
Mermaid	Diagramming language	Everyone

Instead of asking Which one should we use?, ask:

What question are we trying to answer?

EDGY Starts with the Enterprise

Before discussing applications, APIs, or cloud platforms, organizations need to understand themselves.

Questions like these belong at the enterprise level:

* Why do we exist?
* What value do we create?
* Which capabilities differentiate us?
* Who are our stakeholders?
* Which products deliver value?

EDGY provides a lightweight way to model these relationships without becoming overly technical.

flowchart TD
    Enterprise --> Capability
    Enterprise --> Product
    Enterprise --> Stakeholder
    Capability --> Value
    Product --> Value
    Stakeholder --> Value

Notice that technology is almost invisible. That’s intentional. Enterprise architecture should start with the business—not the applications.

C4 Takes You into the Solution

Eventually strategy becomes implementation. At that point, software architecture needs a different viewpoint.

C4 organizes software architecture into four increasingly detailed views.

flowchart TB
    Context["Level 1<br/>Context"]
    Container["Level 2<br/>Containers"]
    Component["Level 3<br/>Components"]
    Code["Level 4<br/>Code"]
    Context --> Container
    Container --> Component
    Component --> Code

Each view answers a different question.

Level	Question
Context	Where does the system fit?
Container	What are the major building blocks?
Component	How is each container organized?
Code	How is the implementation structured?

Rather than trying to explain everything in one diagram, C4 encourages multiple focused viewpoints for different audiences.

Mermaid Brings Architecture to Life

Neither EDGY nor C4 defines how diagrams should be created. That’s where Mermaid fits.

Because Mermaid diagrams are plain text, they integrate naturally with Markdown, Git, GitHub, and static site generators.

A diagram becomes just another file in your repository.

flowchart LR
    Architect --> Markdown
    Markdown --> Git
    Git --> Website
    Website --> Readers

This makes architecture documentation easier to review, easier to maintain, and easier to evolve alongside the systems it describes.

They Work Better Together

Rather than choosing one approach, combine them.

A typical architecture journey might look like this.

flowchart TB
    Strategy["Enterprise Strategy"]
    Capability["Capabilities"]
    Products["Products"]
    Domains["Business Domains"]
    Context["C4 Context"]
    Containers["C4 Containers"]
    Components["C4 Components"]
    Deployment["Deployment"]
    Strategy --> Capability
    Capability --> Products
    Products --> Domains
    Domains --> Context
    Context --> Containers
    Containers --> Components
    Components --> Deployment

Each layer adds more detail while preserving the context established by the previous one.

Executives don’t need component diagrams.

Developers don’t need capability maps.

Architects connect the two.

Don’t Force One Tool to Solve Every Problem

Many architecture repositories become difficult to navigate because every question is answered using the same diagram style.

Capability maps become application diagrams.

Integration diagrams become deployment diagrams.

Context diagrams become enterprise strategy documents.

Eventually every diagram tries to explain everything—and ends up explaining nothing.

Good architecture is about choosing the right viewpoint for the audience.

